ed, as are their potentially liberating (and potentially negative) impacts. In line with the Social Work in Practice series style, the book allows readers to explore issues in depth. It focuses on knowledge transmission, and the encouragement of critical reflection on practice. Each chapter is built around 'real-life' case scenarios using a problem-based learning approach. This book is the first to deal with social work and religion so comprehensively and will therefore be essential reading not only for social work students, but also for practitioners in a range of areas, social work academics and researchers in the UK and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aReligion. 0aSocial servicexReligious aspects. 0aSocial service. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aGilligan, Philip, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995z9783111196213oZDB-23-BUPP0 cprintz978186134981140uhttps://doi.org/10.56687/9781447342700?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447342700423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447342700/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-BUPPc1995d2013